Classlass,<br><br>
John is right.   The world stopped when a SAR was initiated.  Airplanes in the air, troops moving, safe zones secured.  No effort was spared.  Unfortunately the enemy knew this and used our on ELTs against us.<br><br>
I myself am from the strategic reconnaissance group.  Our training and knowledge gave us secrets that went way beyond the boundaries of the war.  They were also exposed to information, which strategically located a lot of assets and missions and target priorities.  There is a great deal about that region which had nothing to do with the war that others will never know.  Many of us held clearances, which exposed us to nuclear war plans, contingencies and cryptographic material and civilian agents. Even the clearances were classified. I have had men on board that would hand me a list of those areas they could not over fly. The VC didn't want these men, but the Russians did.  Nice Barter chip don't you think.<br><br>
We went were we had to.   Anywhere.  Aircraft were not allowed to carry any offensive explosive weapons.  Our world was the world of electronics.<br><br>
Even now one of my best friends whom I see daily was one of the EB66 pilots (E is for electronic).  We were in the same unit for years and retired together to work for the Navy.<br><br>
There was another war going on with the &quot;Silent Warriors&quot;.  It still continues today.  No more can be said.<br><br>
All men were worth the effort, but others would cause more damage.  Death was an easier option (that was my plan).  The intent was to ensure that they were not captured alive or who they had to determine the collateral damage.<br><br>
Someday your question can be answered, but not yet.<br>

